instruction:
A `record` is an immutable data carrier. One line replaces: constructor, getters, equals, hashCode, toString:

```java
record Point(int x, int y) {}
// Creates: Point(int x, int y) constructor, .x(), .y(), toString, equals, hashCode
```

Run this — see how little code it takes.

starter:
public class Main {
    record Point(double x, double y) {
        // Compact constructor for validation:
        Point {
            if (Double.isNaN(x) || Double.isNaN(y)) throw new IllegalArgumentException("NaN not allowed");
        }

        double distanceTo(Point other) {
            return Math.sqrt(Math.pow(x - other.x, 2) + Math.pow(y - other.y, 2));
        }
    }

    record Person(String name, int age) {}

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Point p1 = new Point(0, 0);
        Point p2 = new Point(3, 4);

        System.out.println(p1);          // auto toString!
        System.out.println(p2.x());      // auto getter!
        System.out.printf("Distance: %.1f%n", p1.distanceTo(p2));

        Person alice = new Person("Alice", 30);
        Person twin  = new Person("Alice", 30);
        System.out.println(alice);          // auto toString
        System.out.println(alice.equals(twin)); // auto equals!
    }
}

instruction:
Text blocks (Java 15+) make multi-line strings readable:

```java
String json = """
    {
        "name": "Alice",
        "age": 30
    }
    """;
```

No more escape characters for quotes. Indentation is relative to the closing `"""`.

starter:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Before text blocks:
        String oldWay = "{\n    \"name\": \"Alice\",\n    \"age\": 30\n}";

        // With text blocks:
        String jsonBody = """
            {
                "name": "Alice",
                "age": 30,
                "roles": ["admin", "editor"]
            }
            """;

        String html = """
            <html>
                <body>
                    <h1>Hello, Java!</h1>
                </body>
            </html>
            """;

        System.out.println(jsonBody.trim());
        System.out.println("---");
        System.out.println(html.trim());
    }
}

public class Main {
    sealed interface Shape permits Circle, Rectangle, Triangle {}
    record Circle   (double radius)          implements Shape {}
    record Rectangle(double width, double height) implements Shape {}
    record Triangle (double base,  double height) implements Shape {}

    static double area(Shape shape) {
        return switch (shape) {
            case Circle    c -> Math.PI * c.radius() * c.radius();
            case Rectangle r -> r.width() * r.height();
            case Triangle  t -> 0.5 * t.base() * t.height();
            // No default needed — sealed class: compiler knows all cases!
        };
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Shape[] shapes = {new Circle(5), new Rectangle(4, 6), new Triangle(3, 8)};
        for (Shape s : shapes) {
            System.out.printf("%s: %.2f%n", s.getClass().getSimpleName(), area(s));
        }
    }
}

instruction:
Java 21 brings full pattern matching in switch:

```java
switch (obj) {
    case Integer i -> "int: " + i;
    case String s  -> "string: " + s;
    case null      -> "null";
    default        -> "other";
}
```

Combine with `when` for guards.

starter:
public class Main {
    sealed interface Payment permits CreditCard, Cash, Crypto {}
    record CreditCard(String holder, double limit) implements Payment {}
    record Cash(double amount)                     implements Payment {}
    record Crypto(String coin, double amount)      implements Payment {}

    static String processPayment(Payment p, double total) {
        return switch (p) {
            case CreditCard c when c.limit() >= total ->
                "Charging $" + total + " to " + c.holder() + "'s card";
            case CreditCard c ->
                "Declined: limit $" + c.limit() + " < $" + total;
            case Cash cash when cash.amount() >= total ->
                "Cash payment: $" + total + ", change: $" + (cash.amount() - total);
            case Cash cash ->
                "Insufficient cash: $" + cash.amount();
            case Crypto(var coin, var amount) ->
                "Crypto: " + amount + " " + coin;
        };
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(processPayment(new CreditCard("Alex", 500), 200));
        System.out.println(processPayment(new CreditCard("Bob",   50), 200));
        System.out.println(processPayment(new Cash(100), 80));
        System.out.println(processPayment(new Crypto("BTC", 0.005), 300));
    }
}

instruction:
Virtual threads (Java 21) are lightweight — you can have MILLIONS:

```java
try (var executor = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()) {
    executor.submit(() -> { /* task */ });
}
```

Each task gets its own virtual thread — no thread pool needed. Perfect for I/O-heavy work.

starter:
import java.util.concurrent.*;
import java.util.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        int taskCount = 10_000;
        List<Future<Integer>> futures = new ArrayList<>();

        long start = System.currentTimeMillis();

        try (ExecutorService executor = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()) {
            for (int i = 0; i < taskCount; i++) {
                final int taskId = i;
                futures.add(executor.submit(() -> {
                    Thread.sleep(10);  // simulate I/O
                    return taskId * 2;
                }));
            }
        }

        long sum = 0;
        for (var f : futures) sum += f.get();

        long elapsed = System.currentTimeMillis() - start;
        System.out.println("Tasks: " + taskCount);
        System.out.println("Sum correct: " + (sum == (long)(taskCount-1)*taskCount));
        System.out.println("Fast (virtual threads!): " + (elapsed < 3000));
    }
}
